@node wot "what it is"
This is a sort of abstract space render in povray, showing the
level of detail that can be obtained with povray.  Included is
a .pov source file and an iff file.  This render is public domain,
so please copy it and use peices of it in your own renders.  Have
fun with it!!!
@endnode

@node notez "notes"
As I have been working with the Amiga version of povray, I have
noticed a few things not mentioned in the manual that I thought
I'de mention here.

 @{"povray speed" link speed}
 @{"style" link style}
@endnode

@node speed "povray slow?"
If you have a 68030 with a math coprocessor or a 68040, you
should @{b}not@{ub} download the '030 or '040 versions of povray.
Contrary to the descriptions, these versions were compiled
without the coprocessor option.  Anyway, the FPU version of
povray, even though compiled for a vanella 68000 with FPU,
will run (on a 68040) roughly 4 times as fast as the 68040
version!
@endnode

@node style "proper coding style"
So many people use a sloppy hard to read coding style in their
povray source files.  Povray is a language like any other in
that proper style is important.  As with C, don't indent each
level with a tab.  For even a moderately complex render, you'll
tab yourself off of the right side of the screen.  Use two or
three spaces instead!!  You can see this in the included .pov
file.
@endnode
